This is a perfectly normal reaction to the atmosphere. These splits can look alarmingly wide and deep, but in the context of the whole beam thickness, they are not considered excessive: Generally they will not exceed 15-20mm wide, and depth will rarely exceed half the radius of the beam. Even at their extremes, these splits will not compromise the strength of the beam as they do not run far or deep enough to affect the structural integrity. It may however be necessary to maintain the surface of the beams by sanding smooth any splinters or scaling caused by the surface lifting.

The poles are essentially whole tree trunks which are then trimmed to size and pressure treated with a chemical to inhibit rot and infestation. Wood is a natural material that will expand and contract with ambient moisture conditions - hence these round poles also have a natural propensity to open up in “splits” around their surface as they lose moisture in dry and sunny conditions.

These splits are an inherent possibility with any product constructed of round poles – and all manufacturers of round pole items experience queries regarding splits from consumers.
